Jesus heals a man who could not walk.
A few days later, Jesus again entered Capernaum, and the people heard that he had returned to his hometown.
A large crowd gathered, so that there was no room left, not even outside the door. And Jesus preached the word to them.
Four of those who came were carrying a man who could not walk.
But they could not get near Jesus because of the crowd. So they made an opening in the roof above Jesus and, after digging out the tiles, they lowered the mat on which the paralyzed man was lying.
Jesus saw their faith, and he said to the man, "Child, your sins are forgiven."
Some Sharia teachers were sitting there. They were thinking,
Why is this man talking like this? He's saying something very evil! Only God forgives sins!
Immediately Jesus knew in his spirit that they were contemplating this in their hearts, and he said to them, "Why are you thinking about these things in your hearts?
Is it easier to say to this man, 'Your sins are forgiven,' or to say, 'Get up, take your bed and walk'?
"I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins." Then Jesus spoke to the man who could not walk.
He said to him, "I say to you, rise, take up your mat, and go to your house."
The man rose and took up his mat. Then he walked away, while everyone watched. All the people were amazed. They praised God and said, "We have never seen anything like this before!" Jesus chooses Levi.
Jesus went out again beside the Sea of Galilee, and a great multitude came to him, and he taught them.
As Jesus walked along, he saw Levi, the son of Alphaeus, sitting at the tax collector's booth. "Follow me," he told him, and Levi got up and followed him.
Later, Jesus was dining at the home of Levi. Many tax collectors and "sinners" were eating with him and his disciples. They were part of the large crowd that followed Jesus.
There were some teachers of the law who were Pharisees. They saw Jesus eating with "sinners" and tax collectors. So they asked his disciples, "Why does he eat with tax collectors and 'sinners'?"
Jesus heard this and said to them, "Those who are well have no need of a physician, but those who are sick; I came not to call the righteous, but sinners, to repentance." Jesus is asked about fasting.
The disciples of John and the Pharisees fast often and pray. Some people came to Jesus and said to him, "The disciples of John fast and pray, and the disciples of the Pharisees fast and pray. But yours do not fast. Why do they not fast?"
Jesus answered, "How can the guests of the bridegroom fast while the bridegroom is with them? As long as they have the bridegroom with them, they cannot fast.
But the time will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them. On that day they will fast.
People do not sew a new piece of cloth onto old clothes. If they do, the new piece will separate from the old one. This will make the tear worse.
People do not pour new wine into old wineskins. If they do, the wineskins will burst, the wine will be spilled, and both the wine and the wineskins will be ruined. Instead, they pour new wine into new wineskins. "Jesus is Lord of the Sabbath."
On a Sabbath day, Jesus was walking through the grain fields with his disciples. The disciples began to pluck some of the heads of grain.
The Pharisees said to Jesus, "Look! It is against the law to do this on the Sabbath. Why are your disciples doing it?"
He replied, "Have you never read what David did? He and his men were hungry. They needed food.
It was at the time when Abiathar was high priest. David entered the house of God and ate the showbread, which was lawful only for the priests to eat. And he also gave some of the bread to his men.
Then Jesus said to them, "The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath.
For the Son of Man is lord even of the Sabbath.
Healing on Saturday
Jesus went again into the synagogue. And there was a man there with a withered hand.
Some Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They were watching him closely. They wanted to see if he would heal the man on the Sabbath.
Jesus spoke to the man with the weak and crooked hand. He said to him, "Stand up in front of everyone."
Then Jesus asked them, "What does the law say we should do on the Sabbath? Should we do good or evil? Should we save lives or kill?" But no one answered.
Jesus looked at them with anger. He was greatly disturbed because their hearts were hard. Then he said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." So he stretched it out, and his hand was restored as good as new.
Then the Pharisees went out and began to plot with the Herodians against Jesus, how they might destroy Him. The multitudes followed Jesus.
Jesus went to the Sea of Galilee with his disciples. Large crowds from Galilee followed him.
The people heard about all that Jesus was doing. And large crowds came to him from Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, beyond the Jordan, and the region around Tyre and Sidon.
Because of the crowd, Jesus told his disciples to prepare a small boat for him. This would keep people from crowding around him.
Jesus healed many people. Therefore, the sick were pushing to touch him.
When the people saw those possessed by evil spirits, they fell down before him. The spirits cried out, "You are the Son of God!"
But Jesus commanded them to tell no one who he was. Jesus appoints the twelve apostles.
Jesus went up on a mountainside. He called to him those he wanted, and they came to him.
He appointed twelve, whom he also named apostles, that they might be with him and he might send them out to preach.
They had the power to cast out demons.
So Jesus appointed the twelve. Simon was one of them, and Jesus named him Peter.
There were Jacob, son of Zebedes, and his brother John. Jesus gave them the name Boanerges, which means Sons of Thunder.
And Andrew, Philip, Bartholomew, Matthew, Thomas, and James, the son of Alphaeus. Also, Thaddaeus and Simon the Zealot.
Judas Iscariot was also among them. He was the one who would later betray Jesus to his enemies. Jesus and Beelzebul
Jesus entered a house. A crowd gathered again. It was so large that Jesus and his disciples could not even eat.
His family heard about this. They went to take charge of him. They said, "He is out of his mind."
There were some scribes who came down from Jerusalem. They said, "He is possessed by Beelzebul! He casts out demons by the power of the prince of demons."
So He invited them to come closer and spoke to them in parables, saying, "How can Satan drive out Satan?"
If a kingdom is at war with itself, it cannot stand.
If the family is divided, it cannot stand.
